The business develoipment managers- enagge the client- scout the market landscope etc own the revneue coming in from each site, strategic sales support and SME- is Mike lamgford oupastedOk chat gpt did a terrible job can you help me, build out a very comprehensive step by step high touch onboarding plan and a gantt chart that varies by client to client depending on strategic impact, we should be seen as vunderable or high priority once they are 1-90 days post iniitiation.this ppt is a very primitive version of the detailed onboarding framework i want you to publish for me and gantt chart1 Dec 2025Architected comprehensive onboarding framework with tiered Gantt charts and vulnerability tracking.11sJenny is asking me to help her build a comprehensive onboarding framework and Gantt chart for Diagnexia. She's shared a ChatGPT conversation that produced what she considers a "terrible" and "primitive" version. Let me analyze what she needs:

A detailed, high-touch onboarding plan with clear baton ownership
A Gantt chart that varies by client type (strategic vs. standard)
Recognition that clients are "vulnerable" or "high priority" in the first 1-90 days post-initiation
This needs to be much more comprehensive than what ChatGPT produced

From the documents she shared, the key elements are:

BDMs own revenue/client advocacy but shouldn't be project managers
Mike Langford is Senior Director of Customer Experience (SME/strategic sales support)
Customer Service handles onboarding post-contract
Tech support sets up clients on the system
Automation support handles Diagnexia automation and Prima (wet lab internal system)
Integration team is critical - most clients need digital integration/report repatriation
Case Control and Pathologist Management need awareness of new sites
Strategic accounts need "white glove" project management
Smaller accounts are "rinse and repeat"
Customer Service lead should be on every call/email to know client temperature

The ChatGPT output had the right structure but Jenny says it's primitive. I need to make this:

More detailed with specific activities, not just bullet points
Include timing variations based on account type
Have clear escalation paths
Show dependencies clearly
Address the 1-90 day vulnerability period specifically

Let me create a comprehensive React artifact that includes:

A detailed 10-step framework with expandable detail
A visual Gantt chart component that shows timeline variance by account type
RACI matrix
The "vulnerability" scoring for the 1-90 day period

I'll build this as an interactive React component that shows all of this information in a professional, usable format.Jenny, I can see the gaps in what ChatGPT produced - it's surface-level with no real operational depth. Let me build you something properly comprehensive.
Before I create the full artifact, let me confirm a few things to make sure I nail this:
On client tiering:

Are you thinking three tiers (Strategic / Standard / Low-Touch) or just two (Strategic / Standard)?
For "Strategic" - is this defined by annual case volume thresholds, contract value, market influence, or a combination?

On the 1-90 day vulnerability period:
3. Do you want explicit "health check" gates at Day 30, 60, 90 with defined criteria for escalation?
4. Who owns the escalation if a client is flagged as "at risk" during this period - stays with CS, goes to Mike, or elevates to you?
On Integration involvement:
5. You mentioned Integration needs to be aware from the start - do you want them on the initial BDM discovery call, or just notified immediately after if integration is flagged as needed?
On the Gantt:
6. What's your typical timeline variance? E.g., Standard account = 4-6 weeks to go-live, Strategic = 8-12 weeks?
7. Are there any hard dependencies on customer responsiveness you want built into the timeline assumptions?
Give me these answers and I'll build you a proper operational playbook with:

Detailed step-by-step with actual activities (not just headers)
RACI matrix per step
Gantt with timeline variance by tier
1-90 day vulnerability scoring framework
Escalation triggers and ownership
Handoff checklists between baton holders
i think maybe 3 tiers might be good, we need to bring in if its low touch it might be that they are digital already set up we just plug and play and theyonly ever want to send digital slides maybe, yes strategic is contract amount, and influence ideally one of NHS englashs networks like north west london pathology for example.yes need health checks ontegration team notified by central chat immediatly after first call, then joinging a follow up scoping call for the etchnical sale spiece.yes those timelines look good for gannt, i really need owners in terms of when BDMs hand things off the customer service team ar ethe ground truth heart of all customer lifecycle they should manage 95 %1 Dec 2025Architected tiered onboarding framework with health checks and clear ownership handoffs.Jenny wants me to build a comprehensive onboarding framework with:

Three tiers:

Strategic: High contract value, influential accounts (like NHS England networks - NWLP example)
Standard: Regular accounts with typical complexity
Low-Touch: Digital-ready, plug-and-play, just sending digital slides


Health checks at 30/60/90 days during vulnerability period
Integration team: Notified via central chat after first BDM call, then joins follow-up scoping call for technical sales piece
Timelines:

Low-Touch: Probably fastest - maybe 2-3 weeks?
Standard: 4-6 weeks
Strategic: 8-12 weeks


Customer Service owns 95% of lifecycle - BDMs hand off early and stay as advocates only

Let me build this out properly with:

Detailed step-by-step framework for each tier
RACI matrix
Gantt chart with timeline variance
30/60/90 day health check framework
Clear handoff points
Escalation triggers

This needs to be comprehensive and operational - not surface level like ChatGPT did.
I'll create a React artifact with:

An interactive framework showing all steps with expandable details
Gantt chart visualization
RACI matrix
Health check scoring system
Tier comparison

Let me build this properly.Perfect, that gives me everything I need. Let me build this out properly - a comprehensive operational playbook, not the surface-level headers ChatGPT gave you.Diagnexia Service Implementation PlaybookInteractive artifact Synthesized tiered framework with ownership clarity and operational workflows.Great, I've created a comprehensive interactive playbook. Let me explain what's included and offer some additional refinements Jenny might want.I've built you a comprehensive interactive playbook. Let me walk you through what's now included:
What this covers that ChatGPT missed:
1. Three-Tier Classification with clear criteria - Strategic (NWLP-type networks, >£500k), Standard (typical single-site), and Low-Touch (digital-only plug-and-play)
2. 12-Step Framework with proper operational depth for each step showing actual activities (not just headers), who does what, what gets produced, and the explicit handoff mechanism
3. Integration involvement from Day 1 - they're notified immediately via Chat Space after the first BDM call, then join the Technical Scoping Call before contracting
4. Clear baton ownership - BDM hands off to CS after Step 4 and becomes an advocate only. Customer Service owns 95% of the lifecycle as you wanted
5. Gantt chart that adjusts by tier - Strategic runs 8-12 weeks, Standard 4-6 weeks, Low-Touch 2-3 weeks
6. Health Checks at Day 30/60/90 with weighted scoring criteria and explicit escalation paths (30 → SX Lead, 60 → Mike, 90 → You)
7. Full RACI matrix showing exactly who is Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed at each step
8. Chat Space membership explicitly listed for Step 4 when it gets created

A few things to refine:

Strategic tier threshold - I used >£500k annual contract value. Want me to adjust that?
Low-Touch scope - Should these skip the Technical Scoping Call entirely, or should Integration still do a quick 15-min validation call?
Escalation ownership during health checks - I have it going CS Account Owner → SX Lead → Mike → You. Does that chain work?
Do you want me to add a "Strategic Account" governance overlay with steering committee templates, RAID log structure, and QBR agendas?
Ok now from this can you build me out an interactive playbook for the customer service team...step by step, introduce yourself on X call, ensure they provide you with their SNOMED list, pass this list over to the automation team, make sure they provide you with their X record this in X etc etc2 Dec 2025Architected granular, interactive playbook spanning eight implementation phases.28sJenny wants me to build a detailed, step-by-step operational playbook specifically for the Customer Service team. This needs to be very granular and actionable - not high-level headers but actual instructions like:

"Introduce yourself on the welcome call"
"Request their SNOMED list"
"Pass this to automation team"
"Record this in [system]"
"Send this email template"
"Chase if not received within X days"

This is essentially an SOP (Standard Operating Procedure) for CS Implementation Leads to follow. It should be:

Interactive - they can check things off
Step-by-step with actual scripts/templates
Clear on what to record where
Clear on who to hand off to
Clear on timelines and chase cadences
Tier-aware (Strategic vs Standard vs Low-Touch)

Let me think about the actual customer service journey from their perspective:
Phase 1: Handover from BDM (Step 4 in main framework)

Receive notification in Chat Space that contract is signed
Review Client Handover document from BDM
Create/join dedicated client Chat Space
Assign yourself as Implementation Lead
Review tier classification
Prepare for Welcome Call

Phase 2: Welcome & Pre-Onboarding (Step 5)

Schedule Welcome Call with customer
On the call:

Introduce yourself and your role
Explain the onboarding journey
Set expectations on timeline
Confirm key contacts at customer side
Explain what you need from them (homework)


Send Welcome Pack email with:

SNOMED Code Template
IHC & Special Stains Template
Reporting Proforma Request
Manifest Templates
Shipping Instructions
Portal User Access Form
Portal Manual


Log call in [system]
Set homework deadline
Create chase schedule if not received

I'll focus on the Questionnaire Workshop, tracking critical interactions and team coordination. I'll initiate homework follow-up, ensuring all prerequisites are met before scheduling the workshop. The goal is comprehensive information gathering across multiple internal teams. Key objectives include mapping SNOMED codes, understanding integration needs, and establishing clear communication channels with the customer. I'll meticulously document requirements and facilitate handoffs to specialized teams like Integration and Automation.
For Path Management, I'll consolidate all captured insights into a comprehensive Master Requirements Document, systematically logging every detail in our designated tracking system. This ensures a clear, traceable record of our discovery and design process.
The Design Review phase involves coordinating with the SX Lead to synthesize feasibility feedback from subject matter experts. I'll craft a Draft Service Design document that captures the collective insights and technical recommendations.
During the Design Playback, I'll orchestrate a customer presentation that walks through the entire proposed workflow. The focus is on securing customer validation and establishing a concrete go-live timeline.
Training and Pilot phases will involve structured knowledge transfer, including portal training and controlled testing. I'll closely monitor pilot cases to validate our design and gather real-world performance insights.
Go-Live represents the critical transition point, requiring intensive monitoring and rapid issue resolution. Daily stand-ups will ensure immediate responsiveness during the initial implementation period.
The BAU Transition focuses on sustainable long-term support, establishing a regular review cadence and implementing periodic health checks to ensure continued service excellence.
I'll develop an interactive React component with granular navigation that includes:

Detailed task breakdowns
Dynamic checklist functionality
Integrated communication templates
Automated handoff and tracking mechanisms
Real-time timeline visualization
Proactive reminder systems
Let me build you a proper operational SOP for the CS team - the kind of thing they can actually work from day-to-day.CS Implementation Lead PlaybookInteractive artifact Architected step-by-step customer service playbook with operational checkpoints.I've built a comprehensive CS Implementation Lead playbook. Let me summarize what's included and highlight the key operational details Jenny asked for.I've built you a proper operational playbook for the CS team. This is what they can actually work from day-to-day. Here's what's now included:
9 Phases with granular task-level detail:

Handover & Setup - Receiving the baton from BDM, creating Chat Space, who to add
Welcome Call - Full call script, what to say, questions to ask, how to frame homework
Homework Collection - Chase sequences, validation checks, handoff scripts to Automation/Integration
Questionnaire Workshop - Minute-by-minute agenda, who captures what, post-workshop handoffs
Internal Design & Build - Coordinating SMEs, monitoring build progress
Design Playback - Customer sign-off process, exact scripts
Training & Pilot - Training agenda, dry-run test cases
Go-Live & Hypercare - Day 1 actions, daily monitoring checklist
BAU & Health Checks - Day 30/60/90 scoring criteria, escalation triggers

For each task, I've included:

Exactly what to do (step-by-step actions)
What to say (scripts where relevant)
Where to record it (specific system/doc)
Who to hand off to (with copy-paste handoff messages)
Email templates (click to view and copy)
Tier-specific variations (Strategic vs Standard vs Low-Touch)
Escalation triggers
Checkboxes to track completion

Key handoffs explicitly scripted:

SNOMED list → Automation Team (with exact Chat Space message)
Integration requirements → Integration Team
Reporting specs → Path Management
Routing rules → Case Control
Logistics → Lab Ops

Want me to add anything specific? For example:

More email templates (specific chase sequences, specific scenarios)?
Integration with your actual system names (what's your tracker called, what's your CRM)?
Decision trees for common problems ("what to do if customer misses deadline")?
SLA timelines for internal handoffs (e.g., "Automation must respond within 48h")?
 Opus 4.5Claude is AI and can make mistakes. Please double-check responses.CopyShare

Comprehensive client onboarding framework and Gantt chartSharepdfI need to build the diagnexia scalable low touch playbook and onboarding framework- who hold sthe baton at what point!

The business develoipment managers- enagge the client- scout the market landscope etc own the revneue coming in from each site, strategic sales support and SME- is Mike lamgford oupastedOk chat gpt did a terrible job can you help me, build out a very comprehensive step by step high touch onboarding plan and a gantt chart that varies by client to client depending on strategic impact, we should be seen as vunderable or high priority once they are 1-90 days post iniitiation.this ppt is a very primitive version of the detailed onboarding framework i want you to publish for me and gantt chart1 Dec 2025Architected comprehensive onboarding framework with tiered Gantt charts and vulnerability tracking.11sJenny is asking me to help her build a comprehensive onboarding framework and Gantt chart for Diagnexia. She's shared a ChatGPT conversation that produced what she considers a "terrible" and "primitive" version. Let me analyze what she needs:

A detailed, high-touch onboarding plan with clear baton ownership
A Gantt chart that varies by client type (strategic vs. standard)
Recognition that clients are "vulnerable" or "high priority" in the first 1-90 days post-initiation
This needs to be much more comprehensive than what ChatGPT produced

From the documents she shared, the key elements are:

BDMs own revenue/client advocacy but shouldn't be project managers
Mike Langford is Senior Director of Customer Experience (SME/strategic sales support)
Customer Service handles onboarding post-contract
Tech support sets up clients on the system
Automation support handles Diagnexia automation and Prima (wet lab internal system)
Integration team is critical - most clients need digital integration/report repatriation
Case Control and Pathologist Management need awareness of new sites
Strategic accounts need "white glove" project management
Smaller accounts are "rinse and repeat"
Customer Service lead should be on every call/email to know client temperature

The ChatGPT output had the right structure but Jenny says it's primitive. I need to make this:

More detailed with specific activities, not just bullet points
Include timing variations based on account type
Have clear escalation paths
Show dependencies clearly
Address the 1-90 day vulnerability period specifically

Let me create a comprehensive React artifact that includes:

A detailed 10-step framework with expandable detail
A visual Gantt chart component that shows timeline variance by account type
RACI matrix
The "vulnerability" scoring for the 1-90 day period

I'll build this as an interactive React component that shows all of this information in a professional, usable format.Jenny, I can see the gaps in what ChatGPT produced - it's surface-level with no real operational depth. Let me build you something properly comprehensive.
Before I create the full artifact, let me confirm a few things to make sure I nail this:
On client tiering:

Are you thinking three tiers (Strategic / Standard / Low-Touch) or just two (Strategic / Standard)?
For "Strategic" - is this defined by annual case volume thresholds, contract value, market influence, or a combination?

On the 1-90 day vulnerability period:
3. Do you want explicit "health check" gates at Day 30, 60, 90 with defined criteria for escalation?
4. Who owns the escalation if a client is flagged as "at risk" during this period - stays with CS, goes to Mike, or elevates to you?
On Integration involvement:
5. You mentioned Integration needs to be aware from the start - do you want them on the initial BDM discovery call, or just notified immediately after if integration is flagged as needed?
On the Gantt:
6. What's your typical timeline variance? E.g., Standard account = 4-6 weeks to go-live, Strategic = 8-12 weeks?
7. Are there any hard dependencies on customer responsiveness you want built into the timeline assumptions?
Give me these answers and I'll build you a proper operational playbook with:

Detailed step-by-step with actual activities (not just headers)
RACI matrix per step
Gantt with timeline variance by tier
1-90 day vulnerability scoring framework
Escalation triggers and ownership
Handoff checklists between baton holders
i think maybe 3 tiers might be good, we need to bring in if its low touch it might be that they are digital already set up we just plug and play and theyonly ever want to send digital slides maybe, yes strategic is contract amount, and influence ideally one of NHS englashs networks like north west london pathology for example.yes need health checks ontegration team notified by central chat immediatly after first call, then joinging a follow up scoping call for the etchnical sale spiece.yes those timelines look good for gannt, i really need owners in terms of when BDMs hand things off the customer service team ar ethe ground truth heart of all customer lifecycle they should manage 95 %1 Dec 2025Architected tiered onboarding framework with health checks and clear ownership handoffs.Jenny wants me to build a comprehensive onboarding framework with:

Three tiers:

Strategic: High contract value, influential accounts (like NHS England networks - NWLP example)
Standard: Regular accounts with typical complexity
Low-Touch: Digital-ready, plug-and-play, just sending digital slides


Health checks at 30/60/90 days during vulnerability period
Integration team: Notified via central chat after first BDM call, then joins follow-up scoping call for technical sales piece
Timelines:

Low-Touch: Probably fastest - maybe 2-3 weeks?
Standard: 4-6 weeks
Strategic: 8-12 weeks


Customer Service owns 95% of lifecycle - BDMs hand off early and stay as advocates only

Let me build this out properly with:

Detailed step-by-step framework for each tier
RACI matrix
Gantt chart with timeline variance
30/60/90 day health check framework
Clear handoff points
Escalation triggers

This needs to be comprehensive and operational - not surface level like ChatGPT did.
I'll create a React artifact with:

An interactive framework showing all steps with expandable details
Gantt chart visualization
RACI matrix
Health check scoring system
Tier comparison

Let me build this properly.Perfect, that gives me everything I need. Let me build this out properly - a comprehensive operational playbook, not the surface-level headers ChatGPT gave you.Diagnexia Service Implementation PlaybookInteractive artifact Synthesized tiered framework with ownership clarity and operational workflows.Great, I've created a comprehensive interactive playbook. Let me explain what's included and offer some additional refinements Jenny might want.I've built you a comprehensive interactive playbook. Let me walk you through what's now included:
What this covers that ChatGPT missed:
1. Three-Tier Classification with clear criteria - Strategic (NWLP-type networks, >£500k), Standard (typical single-site), and Low-Touch (digital-only plug-and-play)
2. 12-Step Framework with proper operational depth for each step showing actual activities (not just headers), who does what, what gets produced, and the explicit handoff mechanism
3. Integration involvement from Day 1 - they're notified immediately via Chat Space after the first BDM call, then join the Technical Scoping Call before contracting
4. Clear baton ownership - BDM hands off to CS after Step 4 and becomes an advocate only. Customer Service owns 95% of the lifecycle as you wanted
5. Gantt chart that adjusts by tier - Strategic runs 8-12 weeks, Standard 4-6 weeks, Low-Touch 2-3 weeks
6. Health Checks at Day 30/60/90 with weighted scoring criteria and explicit escalation paths (30 → SX Lead, 60 → Mike, 90 → You)
7. Full RACI matrix showing exactly who is Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed at each step
8. Chat Space membership explicitly listed for Step 4 when it gets created

A few things to refine:

Strategic tier threshold - I used >£500k annual contract value. Want me to adjust that?
Low-Touch scope - Should these skip the Technical Scoping Call entirely, or should Integration still do a quick 15-min validation call?
Escalation ownership during health checks - I have it going CS Account Owner → SX Lead → Mike → You. Does that chain work?
Do you want me to add a "Strategic Account" governance overlay with steering committee templates, RAID log structure, and QBR agendas?
Ok now from this can you build me out an interactive playbook for the customer service team...step by step, introduce yourself on X call, ensure they provide you with their SNOMED list, pass this list over to the automation team, make sure they provide you with their X record this in X etc etc2 Dec 2025Architected granular, interactive playbook spanning eight implementation phases.28sJenny wants me to build a detailed, step-by-step operational playbook specifically for the Customer Service team. This needs to be very granular and actionable - not high-level headers but actual instructions like:

"Introduce yourself on the welcome call"
"Request their SNOMED list"
"Pass this to automation team"
"Record this in [system]"
"Send this email template"
"Chase if not received within X days"

This is essentially an SOP (Standard Operating Procedure) for CS Implementation Leads to follow. It should be:

Interactive - they can check things off
Step-by-step with actual scripts/templates
Clear on what to record where
Clear on who to hand off to
Clear on timelines and chase cadences
Tier-aware (Strategic vs Standard vs Low-Touch)

Let me think about the actual customer service journey from their perspective:
Phase 1: Handover from BDM (Step 4 in main framework)

Receive notification in Chat Space that contract is signed
Review Client Handover document from BDM
Create/join dedicated client Chat Space
Assign yourself as Implementation Lead
Review tier classification
Prepare for Welcome Call

Phase 2: Welcome & Pre-Onboarding (Step 5)

Schedule Welcome Call with customer
On the call:

Introduce yourself and your role
Explain the onboarding journey
Set expectations on timeline
Confirm key contacts at customer side
Explain what you need from them (homework)


Send Welcome Pack email with:

SNOMED Code Template
IHC & Special Stains Template
Reporting Proforma Request
Manifest Templates
Shipping Instructions
Portal User Access Form
Portal Manual


Log call in [system]
Set homework deadline
Create chase schedule if not received

I'll focus on the Questionnaire Workshop, tracking critical interactions and team coordination. I'll initiate homework follow-up, ensuring all prerequisites are met before scheduling the workshop. The goal is comprehensive information gathering across multiple internal teams. Key objectives include mapping SNOMED codes, understanding integration needs, and establishing clear communication channels with the customer. I'll meticulously document requirements and facilitate handoffs to specialized teams like Integration and Automation.
For Path Management, I'll consolidate all captured insights into a comprehensive Master Requirements Document, systematically logging every detail in our designated tracking system. This ensures a clear, traceable record of our discovery and design process.
The Design Review phase involves coordinating with the SX Lead to synthesize feasibility feedback from subject matter experts. I'll craft a Draft Service Design document that captures the collective insights and technical recommendations.
During the Design Playback, I'll orchestrate a customer presentation that walks through the entire proposed workflow. The focus is on securing customer validation and establishing a concrete go-live timeline.
Training and Pilot phases will involve structured knowledge transfer, including portal training and controlled testing. I'll closely monitor pilot cases to validate our design and gather real-world performance insights.
Go-Live represents the critical transition point, requiring intensive monitoring and rapid issue resolution. Daily stand-ups will ensure immediate responsiveness during the initial implementation period.
The BAU Transition focuses on sustainable long-term support, establishing a regular review cadence and implementing periodic health checks to ensure continued service excellence.
I'll develop an interactive React component with granular navigation that includes:

Detailed task breakdowns
Dynamic checklist functionality
Integrated communication templates
Automated handoff and tracking mechanisms
Real-time timeline visualization
Proactive reminder systems
Let me build you a proper operational SOP for the CS team - the kind of thing they can actually work from day-to-day.CS Implementation Lead PlaybookInteractive artifact Architected step-by-step customer service playbook with operational checkpoints.I've built a comprehensive CS Implementation Lead playbook. Let me summarize what's included and highlight the key operational details Jenny asked for.I've built you a proper operational playbook for the CS team. This is what they can actually work from day-to-day. Here's what's now included:
9 Phases with granular task-level detail:

Handover & Setup - Receiving the baton from BDM, creating Chat Space, who to add
Welcome Call - Full call script, what to say, questions to ask, how to frame homework
Homework Collection - Chase sequences, validation checks, handoff scripts to Automation/Integration
Questionnaire Workshop - Minute-by-minute agenda, who captures what, post-workshop handoffs
Internal Design & Build - Coordinating SMEs, monitoring build progress
Design Playback - Customer sign-off process, exact scripts
Training & Pilot - Training agenda, dry-run test cases
Go-Live & Hypercare - Day 1 actions, daily monitoring checklist
BAU & Health Checks - Day 30/60/90 scoring criteria, escalation triggers

For each task, I've included:

Exactly what to do (step-by-step actions)
What to say (scripts where relevant)
Where to record it (specific system/doc)
Who to hand off to (with copy-paste handoff messages)
Email templates (click to view and copy)
Tier-specific variations (Strategic vs Standard vs Low-Touch)
Escalation triggers
Checkboxes to track completion

Key handoffs explicitly scripted:

SNOMED list → Automation Team (with exact Chat Space message)
Integration requirements → Integration Team
Reporting specs → Path Management
Routing rules → Case Control
Logistics → Lab Ops

Want me to add anything specific? For example:

More email templates (specific chase sequences, specific scenarios)?
Integration with your actual system names (what's your tracker called, what's your CRM)?
Decision trees for common problems ("what to do if customer misses deadline")?
SLA timelines for internal handoffs (e.g., "Automation must respond within 48h")?
 Opus 4.5Claude is AI and can make mistakes. Please double-check responses.CopyShare

hierarchicalContent.text:
Architected tiered onboarding framework with health checks and clear ownership handoffs.Jenny wants me to build a comprehensive onboarding framework with:

Three tiers:

Strategic: High contract value, influential accounts (like NHS England networks - NWLP example)
Standard: Regular accounts with typical complexity
Low-Touch: Digital-ready, plug-and-play, just sending digital slides


Health checks at 30/60/90 days during vulnerability period
Integration team: Notified via central chat after first BDM call, then joins follow-up scoping call for technical sales piece
Timelines:

Low-Touch: Probably fastest - maybe 2-3 weeks?
Standard: 4-6 weeks
Strategic: 8-12 weeks


Customer Service owns 95% of lifecycle - BDMs hand off early and stay as advocates only

Let me build this out properly with:

Detailed step-by-step framework for each tier
RACI matrix
Gantt chart with timeline variance
30/60/90 day health check framework
Clear handoff points
Escalation triggers

This needs to be comprehensive and operational - not surface level like ChatGPT did.
I'll create a React artifact with:

An interactive framework showing all steps with expandable details
Gantt chart visualization
RACI matrix
Health check scoring system
Tier comparison

Let me build this properly.Perfect, that gives me everything I need. Let me build this out properly - a comprehensive operational playbook, not the surface-level headers ChatGPT gave you.Diagnexia Service Implementation PlaybookInteractive artifact Synthesized tiered framework with ownership clarity and operational workflows.Great, I've created a comprehensive interactive playbook. Let me explain what's included and offer some additional refinements Jenny might want.I've built you a comprehensive interactive playbook. Let me walk you through what's now included:
What this covers that ChatGPT missed:
1. Three-Tier Classification with clear criteria - Strategic (NWLP-type networks, >£500k), Standard (typical single-site), and Low-Touch (digital-only plug-and-play)
2. 12-Step Framework with proper operational depth for each step showing actual activities (not just headers), who does what, what gets produced, and the explicit handoff mechanism
3. Integration involvement from Day 1 - they're notified immediately via Chat Space after the first BDM call, then join the Technical Scoping Call before contracting
4. Clear baton ownership - BDM hands off to CS after Step 4 and becomes an advocate only. Customer Service owns 95% of the lifecycle as you wanted
5. Gantt chart that adjusts by tier - Strategic runs 8-12 weeks, Standard 4-6 weeks, Low-Touch 2-3 weeks
6. Health Checks at Day 30/60/90 with weighted scoring criteria and explicit escalation paths (30 → SX Lead, 60 → Mike, 90 → You)
7. Full RACI matrix showing exactly who is Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed at each step
8. Chat Space membership explicitly listed for Step 4 when it gets created

A few things to refine:

Strategic tier threshold - I used >£500k annual contract value. Want me to adjust that?
Low-Touch scope - Should these skip the Technical Scoping Call entirely, or should Integration still do a quick 15-min validation call?
Escalation ownership during health checks - I have it going CS Account Owner → SX Lead → Mike → You. Does that chain work?
Do you want me to add a "Strategic Account" governance overlay with steering committee templates, RAID log structure, and QBR agendas?

hierarchicalContent.text:
Jenny wants me to build a comprehensive onboarding framework with:

Three tiers:

Strategic: High contract value, influential accounts (like NHS England networks - NWLP example)
Standard: Regular accounts with typical complexity
Low-Touch: Digital-ready, plug-and-play, just sending digital slides


Health checks at 30/60/90 days during vulnerability period
Integration team: Notified via central chat after first BDM call, then joins follow-up scoping call for technical sales piece
Timelines:

Low-Touch: Probably fastest - maybe 2-3 weeks?
Standard: 4-6 weeks
Strategic: 8-12 weeks


Customer Service owns 95% of lifecycle - BDMs hand off early and stay as advocates only

Let me build this out properly with:

Detailed step-by-step framework for each tier
RACI matrix
Gantt chart with timeline variance
30/60/90 day health check framework
Clear handoff points
Escalation triggers

This needs to be comprehensive and operational - not surface level like ChatGPT did.
I'll create a React artifact with:

An interactive framework showing all steps with expandable details
Gantt chart visualization
RACI matrix
Health check scoring system
Tier comparison

Let me build this properly.

hierarchicalContent.text:
I've built you a comprehensive interactive playbook. Let me walk you through what's now included:
What this covers that ChatGPT missed:
1. Three-Tier Classification with clear criteria - Strategic (NWLP-type networks, >£500k), Standard (typical single-site), and Low-Touch (digital-only plug-and-play)
2. 12-Step Framework with proper operational depth for each step showing actual activities (not just headers), who does what, what gets produced, and the explicit handoff mechanism
3. Integration involvement from Day 1 - they're notified immediately via Chat Space after the first BDM call, then join the Technical Scoping Call before contracting
4. Clear baton ownership - BDM hands off to CS after Step 4 and becomes an advocate only. Customer Service owns 95% of the lifecycle as you wanted
5. Gantt chart that adjusts by tier - Strategic runs 8-12 weeks, Standard 4-6 weeks, Low-Touch 2-3 weeks
6. Health Checks at Day 30/60/90 with weighted scoring criteria and explicit escalation paths (30 → SX Lead, 60 → Mike, 90 → You)
7. Full RACI matrix showing exactly who is Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed at each step
8. Chat Space membership explicitly listed for Step 4 when it gets created

A few things to refine:

Strategic tier threshold - I used >£500k annual contract value. Want me to adjust that?
Low-Touch scope - Should these skip the Technical Scoping Call entirely, or should Integration still do a quick 15-min validation call?
Escalation ownership during health checks - I have it going CS Account Owner → SX Lead → Mike → You. Does that chain work?
Do you want me to add a "Strategic Account" governance overlay with steering committee templates, RAID log structure, and QBR agendas?

hierarchicalContent.text:
Architected granular, interactive playbook spanning eight implementation phases.28sJenny wants me to build a detailed, step-by-step operational playbook specifically for the Customer Service team. This needs to be very granular and actionable - not high-level headers but actual instructions like:

"Introduce yourself on the welcome call"
"Request their SNOMED list"
"Pass this to automation team"
"Record this in [system]"
"Send this email template"
"Chase if not received within X days"

This is essentially an SOP (Standard Operating Procedure) for CS Implementation Leads to follow. It should be:

Interactive - they can check things off
Step-by-step with actual scripts/templates
Clear on what to record where
Clear on who to hand off to
Clear on timelines and chase cadences
Tier-aware (Strategic vs Standard vs Low-Touch)

Let me think about the actual customer service journey from their perspective:
Phase 1: Handover from BDM (Step 4 in main framework)

Receive notification in Chat Space that contract is signed
Review Client Handover document from BDM
Create/join dedicated client Chat Space
Assign yourself as Implementation Lead
Review tier classification
Prepare for Welcome Call

Phase 2: Welcome & Pre-Onboarding (Step 5)

Schedule Welcome Call with customer
On the call:

Introduce yourself and your role
Explain the onboarding journey
Set expectations on timeline
Confirm key contacts at customer side
Explain what you need from them (homework)


Send Welcome Pack email with:

SNOMED Code Template
IHC & Special Stains Template
Reporting Proforma Request
Manifest Templates
Shipping Instructions
Portal User Access Form
Portal Manual


Log call in [system]
Set homework deadline
Create chase schedule if not received

I'll focus on the Questionnaire Workshop, tracking critical interactions and team coordination. I'll initiate homework follow-up, ensuring all prerequisites are met before scheduling the workshop. The goal is comprehensive information gathering across multiple internal teams. Key objectives include mapping SNOMED codes, understanding integration needs, and establishing clear communication channels with the customer. I'll meticulously document requirements and facilitate handoffs to specialized teams like Integration and Automation.
For Path Management, I'll consolidate all captured insights into a comprehensive Master Requirements Document, systematically logging every detail in our designated tracking system. This ensures a clear, traceable record of our discovery and design process.
The Design Review phase involves coordinating with the SX Lead to synthesize feasibility feedback from subject matter experts. I'll craft a Draft Service Design document that captures the collective insights and technical recommendations.
During the Design Playback, I'll orchestrate a customer presentation that walks through the entire proposed workflow. The focus is on securing customer validation and establishing a concrete go-live timeline.
Training and Pilot phases will involve structured knowledge transfer, including portal training and controlled testing. I'll closely monitor pilot cases to validate our design and gather real-world performance insights.
Go-Live represents the critical transition point, requiring intensive monitoring and rapid issue resolution. Daily stand-ups will ensure immediate responsiveness during the initial implementation period.
The BAU Transition focuses on sustainable long-term support, establishing a regular review cadence and implementing periodic health checks to ensure continued service excellence.
I'll develop an interactive React component with granular navigation that includes:

Detailed task breakdowns
Dynamic checklist functionality
Integrated communication templates
Automated handoff and tracking mechanisms
Real-time timeline visualization
Proactive reminder systems
Let me build you a proper operational SOP for the CS team - the kind of thing they can actually work from day-to-day.CS Implementation Lead PlaybookInteractive artifact Architected step-by-step customer service playbook with operational checkpoints.I've built a comprehensive CS Implementation Lead playbook. Let me summarize what's included and highlight the key operational details Jenny asked for.I've built you a proper operational playbook for the CS team. This is what they can actually work from day-to-day. Here's what's now included:
9 Phases with granular task-level detail:

Handover & Setup - Receiving the baton from BDM, creating Chat Space, who to add
Welcome Call - Full call script, what to say, questions to ask, how to frame homework
Homework Collection - Chase sequences, validation checks, handoff scripts to Automation/Integration
Questionnaire Workshop - Minute-by-minute agenda, who captures what, post-workshop handoffs
Internal Design & Build - Coordinating SMEs, monitoring build progress
Design Playback - Customer sign-off process, exact scripts
Training & Pilot - Training agenda, dry-run test cases
Go-Live & Hypercare - Day 1 actions, daily monitoring checklist
BAU & Health Checks - Day 30/60/90 scoring criteria, escalation triggers

For each task, I've included:

Exactly what to do (step-by-step actions)
What to say (scripts where relevant)
Where to record it (specific system/doc)
Who to hand off to (with copy-paste handoff messages)
Email templates (click to view and copy)
Tier-specific variations (Strategic vs Standard vs Low-Touch)
Escalation triggers
Checkboxes to track completion

Key handoffs explicitly scripted:

SNOMED list → Automation Team (with exact Chat Space message)
Integration requirements → Integration Team
Reporting specs → Path Management
Routing rules → Case Control
Logistics → Lab Ops

Want me to add anything specific? For example:

More email templates (specific chase sequences, specific scenarios)?
Integration with your actual system names (what's your tracker called, what's your CRM)?
Decision trees for common problems ("what to do if customer misses deadline")?
SLA timelines for internal handoffs (e.g., "Automation must respond within 48h")?

hierarchicalContent.text:
I've built you a proper operational playbook for the CS team. This is what they can actually work from day-to-day. Here's what's now included:
9 Phases with granular task-level detail:

Handover & Setup - Receiving the baton from BDM, creating Chat Space, who to add
Welcome Call - Full call script, what to say, questions to ask, how to frame homework
Homework Collection - Chase sequences, validation checks, handoff scripts to Automation/Integration

Internal Design & Build - Coordinating SMEs, monitoring build progress

Comprehensive client onboarding framework and Gantt chart

PDF

I need to build the diagnexia scalable low touch playbook and onboarding framework- who hold sthe baton at what point! The business develoipment managers- enagge the client- scout the market landscope etc own the revneue coming in from each site, strategic sales support and SME- is Mike lamgford ou

PASTED

Ok chat gpt did a terrible job can you help me, build out a very comprehensive step by step high touch onboarding plan and a gantt chart that varies by client to client depending on strategic impact, we should be seen as vunderable or high priority once they are 1-90 days post iniitiation.

this ppt is a very primitive version of the detailed onboarding framework i want you to publish for me and gantt chart

1 Dec 2025
Architected comprehensive onboarding framework with tiered Gantt charts and vulnerability tracking.

11s

Jenny is asking me to help her build a comprehensive onboarding framework and Gantt chart for Diagnexia. She's shared a ChatGPT conversation that produced what she considers a "terrible" and "primitive" version. Let me analyze what she needs:

A detailed, high-touch onboarding plan with clear baton ownership
A Gantt chart that varies by client type (strategic vs. standard)
Recognition that clients are "vulnerable" or "high priority" in the first 1-90 days post-initiation
This needs to be much more comprehensive than what ChatGPT produced

From the documents she shared, the key elements are:

BDMs own revenue/client advocacy but shouldn't be project managers
Mike Langford is Senior Director of Customer Experience (SME/strategic sales support)
Customer Service handles onboarding post-contract
Tech support sets up clients on the system
Automation support handles Diagnexia automation and Prima (wet lab internal system)
Integration team is critical - most clients need digital integration/report repatriation
Case Control and Pathologist Management need awareness of new sites
Strategic accounts need "white glove" project management
Smaller accounts are "rinse and repeat"
Customer Service lead should be on every call/email to know client temperature

The ChatGPT output had the right structure but Jenny says it's primitive. I need to make this:

More detailed with specific activities, not just bullet points
Include timing variations based on account type
